    <h1>Eligibility and permissions:</h1>
    <h2>Framework for services on .PUBLIC</h2>

    <p>This DRAFT framework will be designed to enable .PUBLIC to function not just as a
        permissioned space, but as a civic contract.</p>

    <h3>1. Purpose and mission:</h3>
    <p>Why is this institution permitted to operate under .PUBLIC?</p>

    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <p>Organisations must demonstrate clear, verifiable institutional ownership and mission.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Clear declaration of institutional ownership and legal identity</li>
        <li>Transparent organisational structure and funding sources</li>
        <li>Named editorial leads or accountable officers</li>
        <li>Permanent public record of accreditation and changes in status</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Oversight functions:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Regular reviews of organisational status and compliance</li>
        <li>Public reporting on accreditation and oversight activities</li>
        <li>Verification audits at regular intervals</li>
        <li>Public-facing directory of .PUBLIC publishers</li>
        <li>Notification and appeals process for third-party challenges to provenance</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Disqualification trigger:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Failure to maintain a true and permanent public record of ownership, accreditation, unclear institutional
            authorship.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2. Accessibility and inclusion:</h3>
    <p>Who can access this resource, and under what terms?</p>
    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <p>Organisations must ensure universal access to core services and information.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Universal digital accessibility in compliance with [WCAG] standards</li>
        <li>Multilingual provision where appropriate to jurisdiction or remit</li>
        <li>Human-readable summaries of legal and data terms</li>
        <li>No registration walls for essential information</li>
        <li>Pro-active design for access by vulnerable or low-connectivity groups (low-bandwidth environments and/or
            assistive technologies)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Oversight functions:</h3>

    <ul>
        <li>Spot-checks for compliance with accessibility standards</li>
        <li>Annual access audits by third-party assessors</li>
        <li>Inclusion scorecards or public feedback channels</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Disqualification trigger:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Failure to provide multilingual and accessible information, use of registration walls for essential services
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Provenance and attribution: What is this source, and how do we know?</h3>
    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <p></p>Organisations must be publicly accountable for the purpose, intent, provenance,
    accuracy, and transparency of what they share.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Stated organisational mission or objective, whether commercial, non-profit,
            civic, or ideological (to Inform, Educate or Entertain)</li>
        <li>Authorship and publication metadata embedded in each resource</li>
        <li>Formal agreement to uphold .PUBLIC obligations when publishing to the
            domain</li>
        <li>Evident willingness to account for the sources, reasoning, and accuracy of
            published claims</li>
        <li>No capitalisation of .PUBLIC status, nor any misleading implication of
            endorsement by the .PUBLIC network</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Oversight functions:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Published audits of adherence to .PUBLIC publishing standards</li>
        <li>Independent review of applications based on transparency, not ideology or
            intent</li>
        <li>Public correction and dispute resolution mechanisms for demonstrable
            falsehoods, omissions, or misleading interpretation</li>
        <li>Revocation protocols for institutions persistently unwilling to meet minimum
            accountability thresholds</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Disqualification trigger:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Refusal to formally uphold .PUBLIC obligations when publishing,
            demonstrable unwillingness to correct misinformation once publicised,
            absence of embedded publication metadata.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>4. Editorial integrity: Can this information be relied on, and is it communicated
        responsibly?</h3>

    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <p>Organisations must demonstrate ethical communication and editorial standards.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Clear editorial policies published and adhered to</li>
        <li>Separation of commentary and fact</li>
        <li>Transparent correction processes</li>
        <li>No automated amplification systems driven by engagement metrics</li>
        <li>Ethical moderation practices where user interaction is allowed</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Oversight functions:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Community flagging and dispute resolution mechanisms</li>
        <li>Monitoring of correction response rates</li>
        <li>Independent editorial review board for high-risk domains</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Disqualification trigger:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Failure to distinguish fact from commentary, absence of clear correction processes, unresolved ethical
            concerns around external influence.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5. Data handling and privacy: How is data collected, stored, and used?</h3>
    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <p>Organisations must operate under the highest standard of data protection.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>GDPR or equivalent compliance regardless of jurisdiction</li>
        <li>Plain-language privacy policies</li>
        <li>No tracking or fingerprinting for behavioural exploitation</li>
        <li>Secure authentication mechanisms if PII are used</li>
        <li>Strict rules for secure data retention and sharing</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Oversight functions:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Data practice audits by trusted third-party organisations</li>
        <li>Zero-tolerance enforcement</li>
        <li>Annual data impact assessments published in open format</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Disqualification trigger:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Use of behavioural tracking technologies, insufficient disclosure of data practices, lack of accessible
            privacy documentation.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>6. Operational transparency and legal compliance: </h3>
    <p>Is this institution open about how it works and legally sound?</p>

    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <p>Organisations must be open and accountable in their operations.</p>
    <ul></ul>
    <li>Open publication of key institutional policies (editorial, hiring, procurement)</li>
    <li>Public annual report on .PUBLIC obligations</li>
    <li>Compliance with legislation, but in ways that do not breach .PUBLIC principles</li>
    <li>Willingness to submit to arbitration in cases of legal or civic conflict</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Oversight functions:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Publicly accessible repository of public accountability documents</li>
        <li>Mechanism for whistle-blowers or external alerts</li>
        <li>Red-flag list for at-risk institutions under review</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Disqualification trigger:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Breach of .PUBLIC transparency obligations, failure to disclose key
            institutional policies, unwillingness to engage with third-party accountability
            mechanisms.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3></h3>7. Contribution to the Dot-Public value network: Does the institution enhance the
    collective health of the .PUBLIC domain?</h3>
    <strong>Requirements:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Organisations are encouraged to contribute to the collective health of the civic
            internet.</li>
        <li>Use of persistent identifiers and FAIR data principles</li>
        <li>Commitment to publishing under open civic-Ai-compliant licenses</li>
        <li>Participation in peer review, standard setting, or cross-institutional projects</li>
        <li>Shared stewardship of common services like archives, directories, or metadata schema</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Oversight functions:</strong>

    <ul>
        <li>Contribution to indexing (non-punitive but incentivised)</li>
        <li>Federation-level metrics on public value generated</li>
        <li>Tiered participation models for core vs. peripheral actors</li>
    </ul>

    <strong>Disqualification trigger:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>Neglect of FAIR data standards, absence of open licensing.</li>
    </ul>

